Using `important: true` in Tailwind config or the `!` prefix can break third-party component libraries that rely on specificity ordering.

**The problem:**
```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  important: true, // Makes ALL utilities !important
};
```

This causes issues with libraries like Radix, MUI, or Ant Design because their internal styles get overridden unexpectedly.

**Better approach — use `important` with a selector:**
```javascript
// tailwind.config.js (v3)
module.exports = {
  important: '#app', // Wraps utilities in #app selector for higher specificity
};
```

**Tailwind v4 equivalent:**
```css
@import 'tailwindcss';

/* Increase specificity without !important */
@layer utilities {
  /* Utilities already win over component styles due to layer ordering */
}
```

**Per-utility override when needed:**
```tsx
// Use ! prefix sparingly for specific overrides
<div className="!p-0"> {/* Only this utility gets !important */}

// Better: use more specific selectors
<div className="[&.radix-popover]:p-0">
```

Tailwind v4's CSS layer ordering (`@layer base`, `@layer components`, `@layer utilities`) naturally handles specificity. Utilities in the `utilities` layer always beat component styles without needing `!important`. Only use the `!` prefix as a last resort for third-party library overrides.

A multi-step form with animated transitions using Radix Tabs (for step navigation) and Framer Motion (for transitions between steps).

```tsx
'use client';
import * as Tabs from '@radix-ui/react-tabs';
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'framer-motion';
import { useState } from 'react';

const steps = ['account', 'profile', 'review'] as const;

export function FormWizard() {
  const [step, setStep] = useState<typeof steps[number]>('account');
  const [direction, setDirection] = useState(1);

  const goTo = (next: typeof steps[number]) => {
    const currentIdx = steps.indexOf(step);
    const nextIdx = steps.indexOf(next);
    setDirection(nextIdx > currentIdx ? 1 : -1);
    setStep(next);
  };

  return (
    <Tabs.Root value={step} onValueChange={(v) => goTo(v as typeof steps[number])}>
      <Tabs.List className="flex border-b mb-6">
        {steps.map((s, i) => (
          <Tabs.Trigger key={s} value={s} disabled={i > steps.indexOf(step)}
            className="px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium data-[state=active]:border-b-2 data-[state=active]:border-primary disabled:opacity-50">
            {i + 1}. {s.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + s.slice(1)}
          </Tabs.Trigger>
        ))}
      </Tabs.List>

      <AnimatePresence mode="wait" custom={direction}>
        <motion.div
          key={step}
          custom={direction}
          initial={{ x: direction * 200, opacity: 0 }}
          animate={{ x: 0, opacity: 1 }}
          exit={{ x: direction * -200, opacity: 0 }}
          transition={{ duration: 0.3 }}
        >
          <Tabs.Content value="account" forceMount><AccountForm onNext={() => goTo('profile')} /></Tabs.Content>
          <Tabs.Content value="profile" forceMount><ProfileForm onNext={() => goTo('review')} /></Tabs.Content>
          <Tabs.Content value="review" forceMount><ReviewStep /></Tabs.Content>
        </motion.div>
      </AnimatePresence>
    </Tabs.Root>
  );
}
```

Use `forceMount` on Tab content so AnimatePresence can animate exit. The `direction` state controls whether the slide animation goes left or right based on navigation direction.

The `cn` utility is foundational in shadcn/ui and any Tailwind component library. It combines `clsx` for conditional classes with `tailwind-merge` to resolve conflicts.

```bash
npm install clsx tailwind-merge
```

```typescript
// lib/utils.ts
import { clsx, type ClassValue } from 'clsx';
import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge';

export function cn(...inputs: ClassValue[]) {
  return twMerge(clsx(inputs));
}
```

**Why `tailwind-merge` matters:**
```typescript
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';

// Without tailwind-merge: "px-4 py-2 p-6" — conflicting padding
// With tailwind-merge: "p-6" — later class wins, conflicts resolved
cn('px-4 py-2', 'p-6');
// => 'p-6'

// Conditional classes
cn('text-base font-medium', {
  'text-red-500': hasError,
  'text-green-500': isSuccess,
  'opacity-50 pointer-events-none': isDisabled,
});

// Combining component defaults with props
function Badge({ className, ...props }: { className?: string }) {
  return <span className={cn('inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-semibold', className)} {...props} />;
}

// Consumer can override defaults:
<Badge className="px-4 text-sm">Custom</Badge>
// Result: 'inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-4 py-0.5 text-sm font-semibold'
```

`tailwind-merge` understands Tailwind's class groups, so `px-4` gets removed when `p-6` is added (since `p` overrides `px`). Without it, both classes would apply with unpredictable results.

Radix UI's Select component doesn't natively integrate with React Hook Form because it doesn't use a native `<select>` element. The form never receives the selected value.

**Error symptom:** Form submits with `undefined` for the select field.

**Solution — use Controller from React Hook Form:**
```tsx
import { useForm, Controller } from 'react-hook-form';
import * as Select from '@radix-ui/react-select';

type FormData = { role: string; name: string };

export function UserForm() {
  const { control, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<FormData>();

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(data => console.log(data))}>
      <Controller
        name="role"
        control={control}
        rules={{ required: 'Role is required' }}
        render={({ field }) => (
          <Select.Root value={field.value} onValueChange={field.onChange}>
            <Select.Trigger className="inline-flex items-center justify-between w-full px-3 py-2 border rounded-md">
              <Select.Value placeholder="Select a role" />
            </Select.Trigger>
            <Select.Portal>
              <Select.Content className="bg-white border rounded-md shadow-lg">
                <Select.Viewport className="p-1">
                  <Select.Item value="admin" className="px-3 py-2 rounded cursor-pointer hover:bg-gray-100">
                    <Select.ItemText>Admin</Select.ItemText>
                  </Select.Item>
                  <Select.Item value="editor" className="px-3 py-2 rounded cursor-pointer hover:bg-gray-100">
                    <Select.ItemText>Editor</Select.ItemText>
                  </Select.Item>
                </Select.Viewport>
              </Select.Content>
            </Select.Portal>
          </Select.Root>
        )}
      />
      {errors.role && <p className="text-red-500 text-sm">{errors.role.message}</p>}
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

The key is mapping `field.value` to `Select.Root`'s `value` prop and `field.onChange` to `onValueChange`. The `Controller` wrapper bridges React Hook Form's ref-based tracking with Radix's controlled component API.

Tables on mobile need horizontal scrolling with a sticky first column for context. This pure CSS approach works with Tailwind.

```tsx
export function ResponsiveTable({ data }: { data: Array<Record<string, string>> }) {
  const columns = Object.keys(data[0] || {});

  return (
    <div className="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border">
      <table className="w-full text-sm">
